DEFINITIONS OF KEY TERMS
Term
Definition in the Context of the Thesis
Smallholder Farmer
A farmer primarily relying on family labour, cultivating typically less than 5 hectares of land, and whose farming activities are
the main source of livelihood but are often capital-constrained.
Formal Crop Insurance
Risk management products offered by registered financial institutions to compensate for crop losses, including Indemnity- Based (loss verified on-farm) and Index-Based (payout
triggered by an objective index like rainfall).
Weather Index Insurance (WII)
A type of index insurance where payouts are triggered when a specific, objective weather parameter (e.g., rainfall deviation) measured at a nearby weather station exceeds or falls below a predefined threshold, regardless of the farmer's actual yield
loss.
Farmer Resilience
The capacity of a smallholder soybean farming household to anticipate, prepare for, cope with, and recover from external shocks (e.g., drought, pests) without compromising their long-
term welfare, food security, and productive assets.
Value Addition
The process of changing or transforming the raw soybean commodity into a higher-value product (e.g., crushing for oil, milling for flour, specialized packaging) to capture greater
market profits beyond selling the raw grain.
Basis Risk
The risk inherent in index insurance where the index (e.g., rainfall at the weather station) does not accurately reflect the actual loss experienced by the individual farmer on their specific
field.
