2. LITERATURE REVIEW
2.1. Theoretical Review
This study focused on the demand side factors of crop insurance such as farmer’s lack of awareness, lack of trust and premium costs leading to adverse selection. On the supply side it focused on factors such as, insurance company’s challenges in accurately assessing accurate granular weather data, premium pricing and designing appropriate products.
2.2. Conceptual Framework
The conceptual framework for this study illustrated the complex relationships between independent and dependent variables, specifically tailored to soybean farming. Independent variables knowledge and awareness of specific crop insurance type (weather-indexed), trust and premium costs. Also incorporate supply-side factors such as the range of insurance products offered, premium pricing, availability of accurate weather data.
These independent variables are hypothesized to influence the uptake of formal crop insurance among smallholder soybean farmers. The uptake, in turn, is expected to impact smallholder soybean farmer resilience (their ability to cope with climate related and market shocks, and their willingness to invest in improved soybean production practices) and their engagement in value addition activities (e.g., investment in processing equipment, improved storage, direct marketing of processed soybean products like cooking oil or animal feed).
2.3. Empirical Literature
Literature in Zambia consistently found that uptake of formal crop insurance among smallholders is very low, driven largely by awareness and trust issues. In Kasama District, Northern Province, (Kaunda & Chowa, 2023) report that only those farmers who understood weather-index insurance (WII) were likely to adopt it each unit increase in awareness raised uptake by 29% whereas older farmers and those with alternative incomes were less likely to insure. Similarly, Munkombwe et al. (2022) surveyed farmers in Choma, Southern Province, found 34.9% had never even heard
16 | P a g e
of government index insurance offers. These findings echo qualitative evidence that smallholders often do not realize FISP input subsidies include an insurance component. For example, a case study in Mumbwa (Central Province) found “most farmers are unaware that their FISP contributions include an insurance premium”, and those who did claim payouts often received much less than their losses. Across Zambia only about 2-3% of the population uses any agricultural insurance, reflecting severe awareness and accessibility gaps.
Beyond knowledge, social and institutional factors limit uptake. Trust in insurers and simplicity of products are repeatedly cited. In focus groups, farmers stressed the need for local language outreach and trusted intermediaries to explain index triggers. They noted that knowing other farmers who received payouts greatly increases willingness to buy insurance. High perceived basis risk (fear that payouts won’t match actual losses and poor claim experiences under Zambia’s FISP scheme further discourage adoption (Daura & Jangle, 2025, Mwansabamba & Kaliba, 2025). In short, demand-side barriers in Zambia, low awareness, low trust, and a mismatch between products and farmer needs, are well documented. These hinder adoption across crops, including soybeans, though no study has quantified uptake determinants specifically for soybean farmers. Product Design and Delivery Innovations
The literature highlights that formal crop insurance in Zambia has generally been delivered bundled with credit or input packages rather than as standalone retail products. For example, the government’s Farmer Input Support Programme (FISP) now includes a hybrid index-insurance cover on subsidized seed, fertilizer and herbicide. Advisors describes how Pula designed an area-yield index policy embedded in the FISP, it covers drought and pests, reimburses lost seed investments, and pays out when harvest yields fall below benchmarks (Pula, 2025). This product explicitly included maize, sorghum, groundnut and notably soybean under its hybrid index cover. By 2025 Pula had bundled such insurance into the input package for roughly one million smallholders.
Private sector agri-businesses have also pioneered bundled models. In contract farming schemes, buyers pre-finance premiums along with seeds and chemicals. (InsuResilience, 2017) reports that NWK Agri-Services’s cotton scheme offers weather-index insurance (drought and excess rain) plus a small life cover.
17 | P a g e
NWK pre-pays the insurance premium for each farmer, who then repays via the post-harvest sale of output. Any WII payout simply offsets the farmer’s outstanding loan. This model reduced NWK’s risk of farmer “side-selling” (selling to other buyers) and was popular, 52,000 of 70,000 cotton farmers enrolled in 2015/16, and 23,000 received payouts totalling $200k after a drought. GIZ’s LDC cotton project used a similar design, insurance was built into the input loan, so that if a drought triggers the index the farmer’s loan repayment is reduced automatically. The effect was powerful insured farmers took more inputs and expanded their cotton acreage, without incurring debt from failed harvests. These cases illustrate how bundling with credit or outputs can make index insurance viable on thin margins (GIZ, 2025).
Another design approach is insurance linked credit (RCC). An IFPRI case study notes Zambia’s Sustainable Agricultural Finance Facility (SAFF) was planning to bundle loans with index policies so that extreme-weather triggers automatically suspend repayments (the loan repayment insurance or RCC model). This nearly zero upfront cost design can bring more smallholders into formal lending, pilots in Kenya and Ethiopia showed RCC users demanded more input financing than uninsured peers. Policymakers in Lusaka now hope public-private partnerships (e.g. linking insurance firms, banks and cooperatives) will adapt such models nationwide. Notably, though, evaluations stress careful premiums designs must be affordable, indices well calibrated, and product education extensive. Zambia’s insurance schemes are still nascent, and soybean has not been a primary target of innovation, no WII product for soy specifically is reported outside the FISP bundle.
Impacts on Resilience
Studies examining the resilience benefits of insurance show mixed effects. In theory, insurance helps farmers withstand shocks and invest in higher-return practices. For example, GIZ field reports indicate that cotton farmers with index insurance did better, they were willing to invest in improved seed and inputs, and were protected from ruin after drought. (InsuResilience, 2017) notes insured farmers “are willing to plant more cotton” (learning from past payouts). Similarly, the IFPRI/Kenya case (Timu et al., 2025) observes that index insurance can cushion households against alternating drought-flood extremes that otherwise trap them in poverty. Bundled products in Zambia’s pilot programs appear to leverage this logic, insured LDC/LDC era farmers
18 | P a g e
expanded cotton hectares and avoided debt after weather losses, and Pula’s FISP insurance is explicitly justified on climate adaptation grounds (protecting seed investment in erratic seasons).
However, rigorous impact evidence is limited and mixed, (Kayula et al., 2022) conducted a quantitative study among 602 maize farmers and found no significant yield benefit from participating in insurance or finance schemes. This null result may reflect Zambia’s context. Farmers often rely on government input packages (FISP) rather than commercial insurance, so additional products added little beyond the subsidy. More broadly, a nationally representative survey in Zambia (Zambia RALS, 2015/16) showed few existing risk coping strategies actually mitigate rainfall shocks in part because wealthier, educated farmers self-select into the few coping methods that work. Those findings imply index insurance would mostly benefit relatively better off farmers unless paired with extension.
In sum, while contractual models suggest insurance can raise resilience (allowing risk-taking, preventing debt), academic evidence on yield or income effects remains sparse. Crucially, no study has measured how soybean farmers’ resilience (or their ability to invest in farm improvements) responds to insurance access. Soybeans may respond differently than maize or cotton due to its role in rotations and value chains, but this gap is unaddressed in the literature.
Value Addition and Financial Integration
Few sources link crop insurance directly to value addition outcomes, and none focused on soybean specifically. However, the soybean value-chain literature underscored how risk and finance interact. For example, a UNIDO strategy report on Zambia’s soybean sector (UNIDO, 2024), emphasized that farmers gain more from processing the crop than selling raw beans, and identifies lack of credit and high transaction costs as bottlenecks to rural processing. The report explicitly recommended developing new financial tools including insurance and guarantees to de-risk investments in soybean aggregation and processing. It notes that existing digital “paygo” credit platforms have begun bundling loans with insurance for some crops e.g. (maize) but notably not soybean currently. This suggests a missed opportunity, better risk protection could enable smallholder cooperatives to invest in village level oil presses or storage if lenders trust insurance cover.
