By contrast, general analyses e.g. (ifpri, 2025) argue index insurance can unlock higher input use, which in turn may raise production that feeds processing ventures. In the maize-soy system, Griffin Services (an agri-input firm) anticipates that climate shocks driving soybean volatility (prices and yields) are a deterrent to private off-take and processing. Yet none of the reviewed studies empirically examine whether insurance availability would change farmers’ or traders’ investment in value-addition e.g. (fermenting soy into animal feed or oil). In sum, literature on Zambia links insurance to risk mitigation but seldom assesses its ripple effects on downstream value-chain activities. Research in other countries hints at gains from bundling credit and insurance, but application to Zambia’s soybean sector remains speculative.
Policy Context and Research Gaps
Zambia’s policy environment includes significant risk-sharing initiatives, but gaps remain. The government has rapidly expanded FISP insurance cover and launched the Sustainable Agriculture Finance Facility (SAFF) to finance adaptation, yet institutional fragmentation is cited as undermining these efforts. For instance, (Mwansabamba & Kaliba, 2024) show that complex rules and poor communication have left rural farmers confused about insurance under FISP. They call for “more transparent and inclusive insurance processes” as key to climate resilience. On the private side, partnerships (GIZ, IFC) are promoting index based insurance, but uptake stays limited by remaining supply-side hurdles basis risk, data gaps, and affordability. Notably, Zambia’s climate resilience planning e.g. (UNDP, GCF projects) mentions insurance as one tool but focuses on water management and crop diversification, reflecting that insurance is still a nascent element of the national strategy. The experience with FISP WII in Zambia, characterized by in kind compensation and delayed payouts (World Bank, 2019, Smeulders, 2021), demonstrates how design deficiencies can erode farmer trust and hinder widespread uptake. The perception of insurance price by farmers significantly affects uptake (Ngoma & Chowa, 2021)
Crucially, our review reveals a research gap at the intersection of these themes. No empirical study has isolated soybean growers’s response to formal crop insurance in Eastern Province or elsewhere. Most Zambia focused insurance research centres on maize or cotton (often under contract models). Only Pula’s press release and UNIDO’s
