5. DATA PRESENTATION, ANALYSIS, AND INTERPRETATION OF DATA
This chapter presents the empirical findings derived from the field research conducted in the Eastern Province from January 1st, 2026 to January 18th, 2026. The data analysis is based on 200 semi-structured questionnaires administered to smallholder soybean farmers and 15 stakeholder interviews with key informants from Professional Insurance, Madison General Insurance, ZISC, and Nico Insurance. The quantitative data was processed using descriptive statistics in frequency tables using the software Statistical Package for the Social Sciences (SPSS) to perform these descriptive and frequency analyses. While qualitative responses were synthesized to address the supply-side constraints.
5.1 Data Collection and Respondent Profiles
The study utilized a sampling approach covering seven key districts: Sinda, Katete, Kasenengwa, Chadiza, Chipata, Petauke, and Chipangali. The respondent profile represents a broad spectrum of the smallholder sector, with farm sizes ranging from 2 acre subsistence plots to 16 hectare emerging commercial farms. (SEE APPENDIX 3 ON PAGE 32, FOR DETAILED RAW DATA SURVEY FOR 200 FARMERS)
